However,  the  number  of  inputs  for  inducible promoters and gene circuits is still limited, and new orthogonal inducers are needed to  support the construction of more complex programmable systems in the fields of bioengineering  and  biocomputing.  Here,  we  present  two  new  gene  switches  inducible  by  the  antibiotic  simocyclinone D8 (SD8) and the flavonoid luteolin in mammalian cells. Streptomyces antibioticus  Tü  6040  has  evolved  the  DNA  gyrase  inhibitor  SD8,  which,  through  the  bacterial  TetR-like  transcriptional  repressor  SimR,  also  regulates  the  multidrug  efflux  pump  SimX.  Taking  advantage  of  SimR,  as  well  as  the  luteolin-binding  TetR-like  transcriptional  repressor  EmrR  from Sinorhizobium meliloti, we optimized the amounts of transfected genes and DNA operator  sites  to  engineer  highly  effective,  orthogonal  transcriptional  OFF-  as  well  as  ON-switches

triggered by SD8 and/or luteolin. We confirmed that SD8 and luteolin are not cytotoxic at the  concentrations required for switching, and demonstrated the functionality of these gene switches  in  a  range  of  biotechnologically  relevant  cell  lines.  These  switches  were  combined  to  generate  OR  and  AND  Boolean  logic  gates,  and  we  confirmed  their  modularity  by  the  addition  of  the  vanillic  acid-responsive  transcriptional  repressor  VanR  to  generate  a  three-input  AND  gate. This  burgeoning  field  of  research  has  already  led  to  great  progress  in  regenerative  medicine2,3,  biocomputing with the use of Boolean logic4,5 and biomedicine6–8, as well as improvements in product  yield, quality, and cell line development in biopharmaceutical manufacturing9–11. The field of synthetic  biology  was  opened  up  by  James  E.  Bailey,  a  pioneer  of  metabolic  engineering12,  who  applied  the  principles  of  traditional  engineering  to  the  systematic  modification  of  cellular  function  and

metabolism13–15,  and  constructed  a  bistable  genetic  toggle  switch  in  Escherichia  coli  by  using  the  repressors lacI and cI16. Several years later, another report of an engineered toggle switch in E. coli by  Collins  and  colleagues  marked  the  beginning  of  rapid  progress  in  synthetic  biology17,  leading  eventually  to  the  development  of  a  range  of  genetic  toggle  switch  circuits18,19.  Indeed,  many  gene  expression systems enabling programmable gene expression in mammalian cells in response to light20  or  small  molecules21,  such  as  biotin22,  phloretin23  or acetaldehyde24,  are  now  available.  However,  to  design  more  sophisticated  gene  circuits  and  to  enable  more  complex  biocomputing  tasks,  we  still  require new and orthogonal programmable gene expression systems for mammalian cells.  antibiotics.  One  of  them  is  the  aminocoumarin  simocyclinone  D8  (SD8),  which  is  produced  by  the  subspecies Streptomyces antibioticus Tü 6040 and potently inhibits bacterial DNA gyrase25. To protect  itself  from  the  harmful  effects  of  SD8,  S.  antibioticus  has  developed  a  resistance  mechanism,  the  TetR-like  transcriptional  repressor  SimR,  which,  upon  binding  of  SD8,  dissociates  from  DNA  and  allows the expression of SimX, a multidrug efflux pump that removes SD8 from the cytosol26. To validate their application  for this purpose, we first combined the two standard SD8- and luteolin-inducible gene switches used  throughout this study to obtain an OR-gate, in which gene expression is switched ON if one or both of  the inducers are present. Indeed, reporter gene expression was activated in this set-up by adding either  SD8, or luteolin, or both (Figure  6a). Next, we built an AND-gate by combining SimR- and EmrR- specific operator sites in one reporter plasmid (PSV40-OSIMR-OEMRR-SEAP-pA, pDB579). We confirmed  that both SimR-KRAB and EmrR-KRAB were able to suppress expression of the reporter gene in this  scenario and gene expression was induced only in the presence of both inducers (Figure 6b). Here,  capitalizing  on  the  bacterial TetR-like  repressors  SimR  and  EmrR,  we  designed,  built  and  characterized  two  novel  gene  switches  regulated  by  the  antibiotic  SD8  and  the  flavonoid  luteolin.  We  confirmed  that  these  switches  operate  in  a  trigger-inducible,  efficient  and  reversible  manner, thereby enabling precise end-user control of the timing and dosage of gene expression. To  validate  their  potential  for  applications in biocomputing, we demonstrated their functionality in Boolean logic gates, including a  three-input  AND  gate  incorporating  a  VanR-specific  operator  site.  We  also  established  that  the

inducers SD8 and luteolin are non-toxic to mammalian cells in their functional concentration range for  switching,  so  these  switches  could  be  suitable  for  cell-based  biomedical  applications.  Indeed,  the  known  bioactivities  of  SD8  and  luteolin  might  even  confer  additional  advantages  and  potential  for  providing  pSM3169s.
